[{"id":27637,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/825774a3-db3d-45a2-bdb3-1becacb9bd9b.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 94px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/59870980-f498-4bd3-8da1-9138418bff01.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 86px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/90d39f45-43b2-4fe8-aee3-78d4e6e75e56.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 97px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d1a666b5-51ee-4ea3-973d-908ae709c475.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 79px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SOCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is a halogenating agent. The carboxylic acid group of reactant changes to acid chloride. The acid chloride formed reacts with primary amine to give secondary amide. The secondary amide undergo reduction with lithium aluminium hydride to give secondary amine.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5546dec6-cec8-48ad-a320-e802a2d65c26.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 196px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27640,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When salicylic acid is heated with methyl alcohol, the carboxyl group of salicylic acid is esterified producing a strong-smelling liquid ester (methyl salicylate). Aspirin is prepared by chemical synthesis from salicylic acid, through acetylation with acetic anhydride.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/671e3d54-d3fa-47ae-8761-34b1efb27a37-9896850_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 602px; height: 150px;\" />&nbsp;Hence, reagent&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math>&nbsp;respectively are:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27626,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A and D only","A,B and E only","B,C and E only","B and E only"],"answer":3,"solution":"(A) $\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{N} \\xrightarrow[\\text { mild condition }]{\\text { (i) } \\mathrm{H}^{+} / \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{CONH}_2$<br />Under mild condition amide is formed because this reaction is typically slow if further more heat will supplied then it gets convert in to -COOH.<br />(B) $\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{MgX} \\xrightarrow[\\text { (ii) } \\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}]{\\text {(i) } \\mathrm{CO}_2} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{COOH}$<br />(C) $\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{C} \\equiv \\mathrm{N} \\xrightarrow[\\text { (ii) } \\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}]{\\text {(i) } \\mathrm{SnCl}_2 / \\mathrm{HCl}} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{CHO}$<br />(D) $\\mathrm{R} \\cdot \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\cdot \\mathrm{OH} \\xrightarrow{\\mathrm{PCC}} \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{CHO}$<br />(E) <br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/TBqlwFTjkSIABCdcP63HxkIiWKpYn9w9mCCbj3TBRoU.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27688,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH}$","$\\mathrm{HCOOH}$","$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\mathrm{COOH}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":27636,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5a60e685-6dd7-4661-b430-0a8d5f8da08e.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 149px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5760d412-4ce2-4321-9c56-5a17da992a89.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 163px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/43e14125-985a-41d6-96f7-d05813970d5f.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 162px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a56cfc97-addf-48d2-9080-bc3762d93757.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 169px;\"/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Reaction of aniline sulphonic acid with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math> gives diazo ester sulphonic acid. Which on further treatment with naphthalene derivative undergoes diazo coupling reaction to give red azo dye.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4794da58-c530-4672-ad6a-6a7ebfa24171.png\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 270px;\"/></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2cca182a-c4db-4896-828d-ccf85b1c2e1e.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 530px;\"/></p><p>This is known as Griess-Ilosvay test. </p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27689,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{PhCOOH}$","$\\mathrm{O}-\\mathrm{NO}_2 \\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_4 \\mathrm{COOH}$","$\\mathrm{p}-\\mathrm{NO}_2 \\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_4 \\mathrm{COOH}$","$\\mathrm{m}-\\mathrm{NO}_2 \\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_4 \\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27648,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>LiAlH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MnO</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>When benzoic acid is heated with formic acid in presence of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mno</mi></math>, benzaldehyde is obtained.</p><p>The reaction is given below, along with benzaldehyde, carbondioxide and water are also obtained.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>HCOOH</mi><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Heat</mi><mi>MnO</mi></munderover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27678,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>CNCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NCCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CNCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NCCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>ClCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Acidic character <math><mi>&#945;</mi></math> stability of conjugate base (anion)<br /><br />Stability of anion <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math><br /><br />Hence greater the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> effect greater will be the acidity<br /><br />Order of -I-effect <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>CN</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math> Hence, order of acidity &nbsp;will be<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>NC</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi>FCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>COOH</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27642,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/17ad82ca-bd77-4f67-b340-21c05457c7d3-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b142730-f0be-4ce4-b152-aabc79f5e36b-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 110px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc3ad91c-69bf-40d9-876b-adbcf5b5e5ea-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a8d5d272-10a3-43c0-bea7-a0ebe1f758d4-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 80px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>First heterolytic&nbsp;fission of iodine will take place and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;will attack at double bond site. Then oxygen of carboxylic acid will attack on the carbocation, forming a cyclic ring. In last step elimination reaction will take place in presence of heat and Py.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa35534c-b562-42c1-9744-d03fbbf1575d-image.png\" style=\"width: 526px; height: 250px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27684,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9c7283c3-2dd8-42ca-b561-61a2f3b4dfb0-image.png\" style=\"width: 182px; height: 78px;\" />","<math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>CH</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msub> <msub> <mtext>CH</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mtext>COOH</mtext> </mrow> </math>","<math><mrow>  <msub>          <mtext>CH</mtext>        <mn>3</mn>  </msub>  <mtext>COOH</mtext></mrow></math>","<math><mrow>  <msub>          <mtext>CH</mtext>        <mn>3</mn>  </msub>  <msub>          <mtext>CH</mtext>        <mn>2</mn>  </msub>  <msub>          <mtext>CH</mtext>        <mn>2</mn>  </msub>  <mtext>COOH</mtext></mrow></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Ammonia reacts with carboxylic acid to form ammonium carboxylate (B). Which on heating form amide (C). Amide on reaction with bromine and KOH&nbsp;undergo Hoffmann Bromamide reaction to form amine with one carbon less.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow></mrow></mover><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8854;</mo></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8854;</mo></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></mover><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><munder><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>|</mo><mo>|</mo></mrow></munder></mover><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>Hoffmann</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>bromamide</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>degradation</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>KOH</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27693,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["propanoic acid and ammonium salt","ethanoic acid and ammonium salt","methylamine salt and ethanoic acid","ethylamine salt and methanoic acid"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{~N} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}+\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O} \\stackrel{\\mathrm{H}^{+}}{\\longrightarrow} \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{NH}_2+\\mathrm{HCOOH}$. Therefore it gives only one mono chloroalkane.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":27673,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/00kGSxKaFOpGgf9v_g65Oy9JdIoKOoPA4fzH96eFoAY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lUJF9OOv18EqWn5Mcac2FcZCpOGK5yepZHVkZfTrTzA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rTlVfWG62LyH8IxBnHBhH5XOij3bi5ZLKnwad6b7vIQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/XVAigqCcOXIABJyTp_E_qIwUm0URkSB5m-wnKLKm7Rk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eTSGo49aRK-_kmIdm94okiFJcdaZCnoQLOO3k9hoIQo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27655,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["Heating trans-but-2-enedioic acÄ±d","Heating cis-but-2-enedioic acid","Treating cis-but-2-enedioic acid with alcohol and acid","Treating trans-but-2-enedioic acid with alcohol and acid"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Heating cis-but-2-enedioic acid give maleic anhydride as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/03acca85-8093-4fe8-bf94-6d09d8a7fc90-image.png\" style=\"width: 505px; height: 265px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27649,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect.","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The melting point of carboxylic acid has no trend as we can observe from the following data of metling point.</p><p>Methanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Ethanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Propanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Butanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Pentonoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Hexonic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Heptanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Octanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> acid. Water solubility of carboxylic acid decreases as we increase the molar mass &amp; hence hydrophobic part of the chain.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27694,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COCl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CHCOOH}$","$\\mathrm{ClCH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RnKOv31ZXIAr5RihYMyaBE3hQ_f5se7UqkY3V62OVnE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":27672,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In the mentioned structures&nbsp;<math><msup><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> will get added to the carbon having slight positive charge.<br /><br />Presence of <math><mtext>C</mtext><mtext>l</mtext></math> increases the positive charge whereas an electron donating group like <math><mtext>N</mtext><msub><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> decreases the tendency.<br /><br />Rate of reaction <math><mo>&#8733;</mo></math> <math><mo>-</mo><mtext>M</mtext></math> or <math><mo>-</mo><mtext>I</mtext></math> group<br /><br />Rate of reaction <math><mo>&#8733;</mo></math> <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math> and <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo><mtext>I</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br />Hence, the correct order will be:<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b5c0226c-a62e-42a7-8d33-561f2092b726-image.png\" style=\"width: 565px; height: 141px;\" /></p><p><img height=\"142\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8c61ef6-c2c1-4121-8e4b-9a055c04bd3f-image.png\" width=\"450\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27633,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Major product B is $\\rightarrow$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uDQz7Od7wcNvPL5SEFlPOYKdUmi9Ys-ewMJDxeJAxIs.original.fullsize.png\"><br />Total number of $\\pi$ bonds in $B$ are 5","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27622,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$A>D>B>C$","$C>A>D>B$","$C>B>A>D$","$A>D>C>B$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Product [A]: From PhNH₂, steps (1) NaNO₂ + HCl forms diazonium salt, (2) CuCN gives benzonitrile, (3) H₃O⁺/Δ hydrolyzes to benzoic acid (PhCOOH), pKa ≈ 4.2.<br>Product [B]: From CH₃CH₂CHO, Tollens' oxidation with $[Ag(NH_3)_2]^+$ produces acetic acid (CH₃COOH), pKa ≈ 4.8.<br>Product [C]: From CH₄ + O₂ with heat and Na₂Cr₂O₇/H⁺ produces formic acid (HCOOH), pKa ≈ 3.8 (strongest acid).<br>Product [D]: From PhCH₂MgBr + CO₂, the Grignard reaction produces phenylacetic acid (PhCH₂COOH), pKa ≈ 4.3.<br>Acidic strength order (lower pKa = stronger): C (3.8) > A (4.2) > D (4.3) > B (4.8).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27669,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5df8221c-3249-4529-8ad1-88b27a95ea61-image.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 191px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d252b9e2-d1a6-41c5-aecd-4a1d01cd3831-image.png\" style=\"width: 220px; height: 168px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9f1771c2-1830-416b-9fc1-543fc7713766-image.png\" style=\"width: 198px; height: 193px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c28d38bc-edae-48c6-91f9-405c656c945f-image.png\" style=\"width: 198px; height: 165px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fa24b981-1e51-464a-91f4-ca9a8105a734-image26.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 149px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/29c89d64-42d8-4329-b583-755118e1418e-image27.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 250px;\" /><br />Acid catalyzed hydrolysis of ester followed by esterification to give a six membered ring.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27660,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>COOH</mi></math>&nbsp;group present in</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21ddb3e9-c950-4dc5-8e6c-088424aea058-01bd4eb6-60d5-499f-983a-bf9d87e7851f-image.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 458px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27620,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["2-Chloropropanoic acid","3-Chloropropanoic acid","1-Chloropropane","2-Chloropropane"],"answer":0,"solution":"Step 1: Hydrolysis of the nitrile.<br>Propanenitrile on basic hydrolysis followed by acidic workup gives propanoic acid:<br>$CH_3-CH_2-C \\equiv N \\xrightarrow[(ii)\\ H_3O^+]{(i)\\ OH^-/H_2O/\\Delta} CH_3-CH_2-COOH$<br><br>Step 2: Hell$-$Volhard$-$Zelinsky (HVZ) reaction.<br>Propanoic acid has an $sp^3$ $\\alpha$-carbon bearing two $\\alpha$-hydrogens. In the HVZ reaction, $Cl_2$ in the presence of red phosphorus selectively replaces one $\\alpha$-hydrogen by chlorine, giving the $\\alpha$-chloro acid after aqueous workup:<br>$CH_3-CH_2-COOH \\xrightarrow[(iv)\\ H_2O]{(iii)\\ Cl_2/\\text{Red P}} CH_3-CH(Cl)-COOH$<br><br>Hence, the major product $P$ is $2$-chloropropanoic acid, which corresponds to option $(1)$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27624,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c_n0EjvFgKMuxdALDlJFAU2HhP58wehMW_XMTXwaDME.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/P7wbZ-bHgm1Ui0BqxGlSgAq4vDkTS6UpQi0ZVOcSyGI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/v4apkzB6hZn1arP9pp-AkvyLpTACuDz5Zi-5ER28AaU.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dub3OcY7XY4044kcOJMKLFUeGnxCdNzHByLN7Zn4Jog.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Concept - Those compounds which are more acidic than $\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3$ can gives effervescence of $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ with aq. $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$.<br />Release $\\mathrm{CO}_2 \\uparrow$ gas with aq. NaHCO 3<br />$\\Rightarrow[\\text { A.S. }]_{\\text {Comp. }} \\gt [\\text { A.S. }]_{\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3}$<br />$\\rightarrow$ Option 1,2 and 3 gives effervescence of $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ gas with $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$<br />$\\rightarrow$ Option (4) Not gives $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ gas with $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27685,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}$","$\\mathrm{HCHO}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Esterification reaction is involved\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8-urAjhehmsKRijWUmrGimh4x731aCiK4R5VOBBrmzU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":27625,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["D","A","B","C"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/O_8Io7VV57ec8Mhu_ZEhR2PDOMMFJIVMD-assmasFTQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />C.B. of terminal alkyne will be sp hybridisation and loculised. In other C.B. will be resonance stablised.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27641,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The&nbsp;trisubstituted compound &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39;, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;gives neutral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;test positive, means the compound is phenol. Phenol on&nbsp;treatment with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi></math> gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>11</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>. The given&nbsp;compound is reacting with hot conc. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> gives a compound <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>. The reaction is Cannizzaro&#39;s reaction. Hence, compound must be&nbsp;benzaldehyde derivative. Compound &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&#39; also decolourises alkaline <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>, means compound contains an alkyl group attached to benzene ring. Hence, the structure of the compound can be written as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bbeffd61-56c1-4021-9be7-c9e485b6310c-image.png\" style=\"width: 236px; height: 222px;\" /></p><p>The reactions are shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d4e638fa-0ba1-4d68-b78d-78eb3598acb6-image.png\" style=\"width: 441px; height: 169px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/32fc7843-aab9-4637-8c93-33413037faf0-image.png\" style=\"width: 656px; height: 175px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0a84fd7d-e596-4a39-b4d2-602f88beebd9-image.png\" style=\"width: 493px; height: 165px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27681,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71c6330d-31e4-4fdc-8ffa-a9a085be0624-image.png\" style=\"width: 122px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/64e71f11-9d15-486e-a8b5-e0f7fa9c3a5a-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/adbeb9f2-d1b3-409c-9e75-3953380b66b8-image.png\" style=\"width: 121px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/33e701db-30f2-4d96-81de-505b434c4ac0-image.png\" style=\"width: 110px; height: 135px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/448bb025-0c1c-47f1-8abf-c266f31a6e64-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 124px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27652,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>(a) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math> (Hydrolysis of ester)</p><p>(b) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><mi>DIBAL</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math> (Reduction of ester)</p><p>(c) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>SnCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math> (Reduction followed by hydrolysis)</p><p>(d)&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1ecc96e1-eabc-41d6-8516-182cdaefd424-image.png\" style=\"width: 435px; height: 90px;\" />&nbsp;(Nucleophillic addition reaction)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27686,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["benzophenone","acetophenone","benzoic acid","benzyl alcohol"],"answer":2,"solution":"Any aliphatic carbon with hydrogen attached to it, in combination with benzene ring, will be oxidized to benzoic acid by $\\mathrm{KMnO}_4 / \\mathrm{H}^{+}$.\nHence, (C) is correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":27680,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["(i) $\\mathrm{NaBH}_4$, (ii) Raney $\\mathrm{Ni} / \\mathrm{H}_2$, (iii) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$","(i) $\\mathrm{LiAlH}_4$, (ii) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$","(i) $\\mathrm{B}_2 \\mathrm{H}_6$, (ii) $\\mathrm{DIBAL-H}$, (iii) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$","(i) $\\mathrm{B}_2 \\mathrm{H}_6$, (ii) $\\mathrm{SnCl}_2 / \\mathrm{HCl}$, (iii) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{O}^{+}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/DqPDNn_rT2INu968wTx25q8PxzHtySEZCcbtVk5tVr8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":27629,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["A, C and D Only","A, B and E Only","A and C Only","A and B Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{A}, \\mathrm{C}, \\mathrm{D}$ produce $\\mathrm{CO}_2$ with aqueous $\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$ solution.\nA, C, D acids are stronger acid than $\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3$ (Carbonic acid)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]